- ## TripleBit
#TripleBit #Approaches #Centralized #Triple #Stores #Knowledge #Graphs 
TripleBit generates the query plan based on the shape of the query and adjusts the plan through a heuristic algorithm. This kind of query plan is usually a left- deep tree [4], which may encounter large overhead when the query is complex. In addition, some centralized RDF query systems also have some optimizations in query execution. TripleBit uses the bitmap matrix to store the data and chunk- based index to help locate data quickly

- ## Distributed
#Distributed #Triple #Stores #Knowledge #Graphs 
Many distributed RDF query systems [10] [11] [12] have been proposed to process large-scale RDF data.

- ## Distributed
#Distributed #Triple #Stores #Knowledge #Graphs 
Since the data is distributed at different nodes, the communication overhead between nodes is often the main reason for performance loss. Therefore, instead of dividing the RDF data set, DREAM [13] decomposes the SPARQL query and merges the result sets returned from the sub-queries to get the final result. Based on the MapReduce framework, Alexander et al. [14] convert the SPARQL query into a Pig Lation query, then optimize the transformed query and execute it. In the above-mentioned distributed systems, the query optimizations are mainly embodied in the distributed nodes, aiming to reduce the interaction of data between nodes through data partitioning and query decomposition to improve the overall query performance. However, research work on query optimization on a single node is still less, especially parallel query processing.

- ## LUBM
#LUBM #Benchmark #Datasets #Performance #Evaluation #Knowledge #Graphs 
We chose LUBM (Lehigh University Benchmark) [15] and BTC 2012 (Billion Triples Challenge) [16] to evaluate the performance of Grace because they are widely used to evaluate RDF engines. LUBM is developed by Lehigh University. LUBM has a data generator and a set of test queries. With the generator, users can generate any scale of data sets. Here, we generate the data set (LUBM 1000M) with 1.3 billion triples. Different from LUBM which is a synthetic data set, BTC 2012 is a real-life data set that has been crawled from multiple data sources such as Dbpedia [17] and Freebase [18]. The data sets are listed in Table I. As Table I shows, BTC 2012 contains 57,193 predicates while LUBM has only 18 predicates. Furthermore, BTC2012 is smaller than LUBM 1000M. In the experiments, we choose same queries as [7].
